pages.summary: This is an operative report for patient John, Carlos, from Avanguard Surgery Center. The procedure was performed on 12/05/2022 by attending surgeon Ardalan Nourian, M.D. The patient's preoperative and postoperative diagnoses included L5-S1 disk bulge, facet pain, and radiculopathy. The procedure performed was a bilateral L5-S1 facet injection with the use of fluoroscopy. The patient received injections of lidocaine, Marcaine, and Kenalog. There were no complications, and the patient was taken to recovery. The report was electronically authenticated by Alen Nourian, M.D. on 12/05/2022.
pages.extracted_text:
AVANGUARD SURGERY CENTER

OPERATIVE REPORT

PATIENT NAME: John, Carlos

DATE OF PROCEDURE: 12/05/2022

ATTENDING SURGEON: Ardalan Nourian, M.D.

PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSES:
1. L5-S1 disk bulge.
2. L5-S1 facet pain.
3. L5-S1 facet pain syndrome.
4. L5-S1 radiculopathy.

POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSES:
1. L5-S1 disk bulge.
2. L5-S1 facet pain.
3. L5-S1 facet pain syndrome.
4. L5-S1 radiculopathy.

PROCEDURE PERFORMED:
1. Bilateral L5-S1 facet injection.
2. Use of fluoroscopy.

COMPLICATIONS: None.

ANESTHESIA: Local medications with monitored vital signs.

DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE: After informed consent was signed, the patient was brought into the procedural suite. He was then placed into a prone position. All of his bony prominences were well padded. His low back was then sterilely prepped and draped. After a surgical time-out was performed, we then marked out our injection sites and injected the subcutaneous tissue with 2% lidocaine for local anesthesia. Next, a 25-gauge spinal needle was cannulated the L5 and S1 facet capsules bilaterally and confirmed under fluoroscopic imaging. After confirming our facet capsules, we then injected each level with 2 mL of 0.25% Marcaine and 1.5 mL of Kenalog. No bleeding or spinal fluid leak was appreciated. The patient was then taken to recovery room uneventfully.

ALEN NOURIAN, M.D.

pages.summary: This is an operative report for patient John, Carlos from Avanguard Surgery Center. The attending surgeon was Alen Nourian, MD. The patient's pre- and post-operative diagnoses were low back pain, lumbar facet pain, lumbar disc bulge, and lumbar radiculopathy. The procedure performed was a bilateral L5-S1 facet injection with the use of fluoroscopy under MAC sedation. The procedure involved injecting 1% lidocaine for local anesthetic, followed by an injection into each facet capsule of 1 mL of 0.25% Marcaine and 1 mL of another substance (text is cut off). There were no complications reported. No specific dates are mentioned in the document.

pages.summary: This document provides detailed instructions, notices, and agreements for patients and providers related to various U.S. government and private health programs, including Medicare, TRICARE, FECA, Black Lung, and Medicaid. It outlines the terms for payment, the authorization for release of information, and the legal certifications required from both the patient and the physician/supplier for claim processing. The document includes a Privacy Act Statement concerning the collection and use of personal information. It references specific regulatory publications with important dates, such as a Medicare claims notice from the Federal Register dated September 12, 1990, and an OWCP claims notice from the Federal Register dated February 28, 1990. It also mentions the Paperwork Reduction Act of 1995.
pages.extracted_text:
BECAUSE THIS FORM IS USED BY VARIOUS GOVERNMENT AND PRIVATE HEALTH PROGRAMS, SEE SEPARATE INSTRUCTIONS ISSUED BY APPLICABLE PROGRAMS.
NOTICE: Any person who knowingly files a statement of claim containing any misrepresentation or any false, incomplete or misleading information may be guilty of a
criminal act punishable under law and may be subject to civil penalties.
REFERS TO GOVERNMENT PROGRAMS ONLY
MEDICARE AND TRICARE PAYMENTS: A patient's signature requests that payment be made and authorizes release of any information necessary to process the claim and certifies that
the information provided in Blocks 1 through 12 is true, accurate and complete. In the case of a Medicare claim, the patient's signature authorizes any entity to release to Medicare medical
and nonmedical information and whether the person has employer group health insurance, liability, no-fault, worker's compensation or other insurance which is responsible to pay for the
services for which the Medicare claim is made. See 42 CFR 411.24(a). If item 9 is completed, the patient's signature authorizes release of the information to the health plan or agency shown.
In Medicare assigned or TRICARE participation cases, the physician agrees to accept the charge determination of the Medicare carrier or TRICARE fiscal intermediary as the full charge and
the patient is responsible only for the deductible, coinsurance and non-covered services. Coinsurance and the deductible are based upon the charge determination of the Medicare carrier or
TRICARE fiscal intermediary if this is less than the charge submitted. TRICARE is not a health insurance program but makes payment for health benefits provided through certain affiliations
with the Uniformed Services. Information on the patient's sponsor should be provided in those items captioned in "Insured"; i.e., items 1a, 4, 6, 7, 9, and 11.
BLACK LUNG AND FECA CLAIMS
The provider agrees to accept the amount paid by the Government as payment in full. See Black Lung and FECA instructions regarding required procedure and diagnosis coding systems.
SIGNATURE OF PHYSICIAN OR SUPPLIER (MEDICARE, TRICARE, FECA AND BLACK LUNG)
In submitting this claim for payment from federal funds, I certify that: 1) the information on this form is true, accurate and complete; 2) I have familiarized myself with all applicable laws,
regulations, and program instructions, which are available from the Medicare contractor; 3) I have provided or will provide sufficient information required to allow the government to make an
informed eligibility and payment decision; 4) this claim, whether submitted by me or on my behalf by my designated billing company, complies with all applicable Medicare and/or Medicaid
laws, regulations, and program instructions for payment including but not limited to the Federal anti-kickback statute and Physician Self-Referral law (commonly known as Stark law); 5) the
services on this form were medically necessary and personally furnished by me or were furnished incident to my professional service by my employee under my direct supervision, except as
otherwise expressly permitted by Medicare or TRICARE; 6) for each service rendered incident to my professional service, the identity (legal name and NPI, license #, or SSN) of the primary
individual rendering each service is reported in the designated section. For services to be considered "incident to" a physician's professional services, 1) they must be rendered under the
physician's direct supervision by his/her employee, 2) they must be an integral, although incidental part of a covered physician service, 3) they must be of kinds commonly furnished in
physician's offices, and 4) the services of non-physicians must be included on the physician's bills.
For TRICARE claims, I further certify that I (or any employee) who rendered services am not an active duty member of the Uniformed Services or a civilian employee of the United States
Government or a contract employee of the United States Government, either civilian or military (refer to 5 USC 5536). For Black-Lung claims, I further certify that the services performed were
for a Black Lung-related disorder.
No Part B Medicare benefits may be paid unless this form is received as required by existing law and regulations (42 CFR 424.32).
NOTICE: Any one who misrepresents or falsifies essential information to receive payment from Federal funds requested by this form may upon conviction be subject to fine and imprisonment
under applicable Federal laws.
NOTICE TO PATIENT ABOUT THE COLLECTION AND USE OF MEDICARE, TRICARE, FECA, AND BLACK LUNG INFORMATION (PRIVACY ACT STATEMENT)
We are authorized by CMS, TRICARE and OWCP to ask you for information needed in the administration of the Medicare, TRICARE, FECA, and Black Lung programs. Authority to collect
information is in section 205(a), 1862, 1872 and 1874 of the Social Security Act as amended, 42 CFR 411.24(a) and 424.5(a) (6), and 44 USC 3101:41 CFR 101 et seq and 10 USC 1079
and 1086; 5 USC 8101 et seq; and 30 USC 901 et seq: 38 USC 613; .. 9397.
The information we obtain to complete claims under these programs is used to identify you and to determine your eligibility. It is also used to decide if the services and supplies you received
are covered by these programs and to insure that proper payment is made.
The information may also be given to other providers of services, carriers, intermediaries, medical review boards, health plans, and other organizations or Federal agencies, for the effective
administration of Federal provisions that require other third parties payers to pay primary to Federal program, and as otherwise necessary to administer these programs. For example, it may
be necessary to disclose information about the benefits you have used to a hospital or doctor. Additional disclosures are made through routine uses for information contained in systems of
records.
FOR MEDICARE CLAIMS: See the notice modifying system No. 09-70-0501, titled, 'Carrier Medicare Claims Record,' published in the Federal Register, Vol. 55 No. 177, page 37549,
Wed. Sept. 12, 1990, or as updated and republished.
FOR OWCP CLAIMS: Department of Labor, Privacy Act of 1974, "Republication of Notice of Systems of Records," Federal Register Vol. 55 No. 40, Wed Feb. 28, 1990, See ESA-5, ESA-6,
ESA-12, ESA-13, ESA-30, or as updated and republished.
FOR TRICARE CLAIMS: PRINCIPLE PURPOSE(S): To evaluate eligibility for medical care provided by civilian sources and to issue payment upon establishment of eligibility and
determination that the services/supplies received are authorized by law.
ROUTINE USE(S): Information from claims and related documents may be given to the Dept. of Veterans Affairs, the Dept. of Health and Human Services and/or the Dept. of Transportation
consistent with their statutory administrative responsibilities under TRICARE/CHAMPVA; to the Dept. of Justice for representation of the Secretary of Defense in civil actions; to the Internal
Revenue Service, private collection agencies, and consumer reporting agencies in connection with recoupment claims; and to Congressional Offices in response to inquiries made at the
request of the person to whom a record pertains. Appropriate disclosures may be made to other federal, state, local, foreign government agencies, private business entities, and individual
providers of care, on matters relating to entitlement, claims adjudication, fraud, program abuse, utilization review, quality assurance, peer review, program integrity, third-party liability,
coordination of benefits, and civil and criminal litigation related to the operation of TRICARE.
DISCLOSURES: Voluntary; however, failure to provide information will result in delay in payment or may result in denial of claim. With the one exception discussed below, there are no
penalties under these programs for refusing to supply information. However, failure to furnish information regarding the medical services rendered or the amount charged would prevent
payment of claims under these programs. Failure to furnish any other information, such as name or claim number, would delay payment of the claim. Failure to provide medical information
under FECA could be deemed an obstruction.
It is mandatory that you tell us if you know that another party is responsible for paying for your treatment. Section 1128B of the Social Security Act and 31 USC 3801-3812 provide penalties
for withholding this information.
You should be aware that P.L. 100-503, the "Computer Matching and Privacy Protection Act of 1988", permits the government to verify information by way of computer matches.
MEDICAID PAYMENTS (PROVIDER CERTIFICATION)
I hereby agree to keep such records as are necessary to disclose fully the extent of services provided to individuals under the State's Title XIX plan and to furnish information regarding any
payments claimed for providing such services as the State Agency or Dept. of Health and Human Services may request.
I further agree to accept, as payment in full, the amount paid by the Medicaid program for those claims submitted for payment under that program, with the exception of authorized deductible,
coinsurance, co-payment or similar cost-sharing charge.
SIGNATURE OF PHYSICIAN (OR SUPPLIER): I certify that the services listed above were medically indicated and necessary to the health of this patient and were personally furnished by
me or my employee under my personal direction.
NOTICE: This is to certify that the foregoing information is true, accurate and complete. I understand that payment and satisfaction of this claim will be from Federal and State funds, and that
any false claims, statements, or documents, or concealment of a material fact, may be prosecuted under applicable Federal or State laws.
According to the Paperwork Reduction Act of 1995, no persons are required to respond to a collection of information unless it displays a valid OMB control number. The valid OMB control
number for this information collection is 0938-1197. The time required to complete this information collection is estimated to average 10 minutes per response, including the time to review
instructions, search existing data resources, gather the data needed, and complete and review the information collection. If you have any comments concerning the accuracy of the time
estimate(s) or suggestions for improving this form, please write to: CMS, 7500 Security Boulevard, Attn: PRA Reports Clearance Officer, Mail Stop C4-26-05, Baltimore, Maryland
21244-1850. This address is for comments and/or suggestions only. DO NOT MAIL COMPLETED CLAIM FORMS TO THIS ADDRESS.

pages.summary: This is a radiology report from OZ Radiology for patient Carlos John, born on 05/22/1986. The report details the findings of an MRI of the lumbosacral spine performed on 02/03/2022. The findings include a mild decrease in the height of the L5 vertebra, decreased signal intensities in the discs at L4-5 and L5-S1, very mild anterior disc bulging, and posterior indentations on the subarachnoid space. Specific level-by-level analysis from T12 to L4 reveals mild narrowing of spinal foramina and a 1-2 mm posterior disc bulge at L3-4. Possible mild caliectasis in both kidneys is also noted as an incidental finding.

SPINE
MRI OF THE LUMBOSACRAL SPINE:
The exam was performed in the sagittal and axial planes with T1, T2 and STIR weighting. No definite
acute fractures or dislocations are noted. No definite infection or neoplasia is noted. There is mild
decrease in the height of the body of L5. Some of the vertebrae have irregular endplates. There are
decreased signal intensities in the discs at L4-5 and L5-S1. There is very mild anterior disc bulging and
spurring. There are posterior indentations on the subarachnoid space apparently secondary to hypertrophy
of the ligamentum flavum and/or spurring of the facet joints. There is possibly mild caliectasis in both
kidneys.
At T12-L1 no herniation or significant posterior disc bulge is seen. The subarachnoid space appears
normal. There is mild narrowing of the right spina foramina. The exiting nerve roots appear not to be
compressed or displaced.
At L1-2 no herniation or significant posterior disc bulge is seen. The subarachnoid space appears normal.
There is mild narrowing of both spina foramina. The exiting nerve roots appear not to be compressed or
displaced.
At L2-3 no herniation or significant posterior disc bulge is seen. No significant indentation on the
subarachnoid space is identified. The spina foramina appear sufficiently patent and the exiting nerve
roots appear not to be compressed or displaced.
At L3-4 there is approximately a 1-2 mm posterior disc bulge with the right side greater than the left and
there is a corresponding mild indentation on the subarachnoid space. There is narrowing of both spina
foramina. The exiting nerve roots appear not to be compressed or displaced.

pages.summary: This document is page 2 of a radiology report for an MRI of the lumbosacral spine for a patient named John, Carlos, born on 05/22/1986. The service was performed on 02/03/2022, and the report was electronically signed on 02/10/2022. The findings detail posterior disc bulges at multiple levels (L3-4, L4-5, L5-S1) with associated narrowing of the spina foramina and indentation on the epidural fat. The impression confirms discongenic and degenerative changes, highlighting a 3-4 mm posterior disc bulge at L5-S1 and slight displacement of the right S1 nerve. The report is from Harris Newmark III, M.D., a Board Certified Radiologist.

Referring Physician:
DR. TIRSCH

JOHN, CARLOS

Date of Service: 02/03/2022
Sex: M
Exam: MRI OF THE LUMBOSACRAL SPINE

At L4-5 there is approximately a 3 mm posterior disc bulge with a corresponding indentation on the epidural fat and to a lesser extent the subarachnoid space. There is narrowing of both spina foramina. The exiting nerve roots appear not to be compressed or displaced.

At L5-S1 there is a small subluxation with S1 anterior to L5. There is approximately a 3-4 mm posterior disc bulge with the right side greater than the left and there is a corresponding indentation mainly on the epidural fat when measured from the posterior aspect of the body of L5. On one image (4-7) the bulge is possibly slightly larger. There is narrowing of both spina foramina. Both exiting L5 nerve roots and both S1 nerve (which are within the subarachnoid space at this level) appear prominent. The right S1 nerve is slightly displaced. The other nerve roots appear not to be compressed or displaced.

IMPRESSION: THERE ARE DISCONGENIC AND DEGENERATIVE CHANGES AS DESCRIBED. AT L5-S1 THERE IS APPROXIMATELY A 3-4 MM POSTERIOR DISC BULGE WITH THE RIGHT SIDE GREATER THAN THE LEFT AND THERE IS A CORRESPONDING INDENTATION MAINLY ON THE EPIDURAL FAT WHEN MEASURED FROM THE POSTERIOR ASPECT OF THE BODY OF L5 BUT ON ONE IMAGE (4-7) THE BULGE IS POSSIBLY SLIGHTLY LARGER. AT L4-5 THERE IS APPROXIMATELY A 3 MM POSTERIOR DISC BULGE WITH A CORRESPONDING INDENTATION ON THE EPIDURAL FAT AND TO A LESSER EXTENT THE SUBARACHNOID SPACE. AT L3-4 THERE IS APPROXIMATELY A 1-2 MM POSTERIOR DISC BULGE WITH THE RIGHT SIDE GREATER THAN THE LEFT AND THERE IS A CORRESPONDING MILD INDENTATION ON THE SUBARACHNOID SPACE. THERE IS NARROWING OF THE SPINA FORAMINA AS DESCRIBED ABOVE. AT L5-S1 THE RIGHT S1 NERVE (WHICH IS WITHIN THE SUBARACHNOID SPACE AT THIS LEVEL) APPEARS TO BE SLIGHTLY DISPLACED. THE OTHER NERVE ROOTS APPEAR NOT TO BE COMPRESSED OR DISPLACED BUT THIS IS NOT DEFINITE. CLINICAL CORRELATION AND CORRELATION WITH PLAIN RADIOGRAPHS IS RECOMMENDED.

JOHN, CARLOS DOB: 05/22/1986 (38 yo M) Acc No. 12570 DOS: 04/28/2025
Patient is a 38-year-old male who presents today for an orthopedic followup for injuries to his low back. Since the last
visit, patient continues to attend his course of chiropractic treatment. The patient's most updated MRI from four
months ago shows 3-mm disc bulges at L4-L5 and L5-S1 where there are varying degrees of stenosis. It was
discussed with the patient that, given the persistent pain despite multiple treatment modalities, he is a candidate for
L4 to S1 lumbar laminectomy; however, he would like to consider his treatment options. Patient will increase
activities with exercises and stretches to help alleviate the pain. He will followup in several weeks if the pain worsens.
Procedures
LUMBAR LAMINECTOMY/LAMINOTOMY: Surgery can be performed in a surgical facility and the professional cost
is approximately $100,000.00-$160,000.00, as well as additional surgical facility and the anesthesiologist fees. The
surgery is usually followed by extensive rehabilitation services at additional cost. The patient will require pre-
operative clearance within 30 days of the surgery which includes CBC and Chem Panel, Chest X-ray and EKG. The
day of the surgery, the patient will require a lumbar support/brace. The patient's condition remains guarded. The
patient is informed that they made need additional surgery in the future if the pain does not get better including
possible fusion or disc replacement and/or possible spinal cord stimulator trial. I will see the patient for follow-up as
scheduled.
Follow Up

Treatment
1. Others
Notes:
Mr. John is a pleasant 36-year-old gentleman who was in a motor vehicle accident on 12/15/2021. Since the accident,
he has been having continued complaints of neck and low back pain. He initially underwent a series of physical
therapy regimens with only mild relief of his symptoms. MRI of his cervical spine shows some mild loss of cervical
lordosis with a disc bulge at C4-5 and C5-6. If his neck pain continues, he is a candidate for cervical facet injections
from C4 to C6. His biggest complaint continues to be pain in his low back, right worse than left sided. MRI findings
shows a L5-S1 listhesis with a right sided L5-S1 disc bulge. Given his continued complaints of low back pain, we
recommend he undergo a L5-S1 facet injection. Patient is agreeable and would like to proceed with the injections as
outlined per above. We will see him back in a few weeks

Procedures
LUMBAR FACET INJECTION:
These procedures cost approximately $15,000 -17,5000 each, which includes the cost of the surgical facility and the
anesthesiologist. Professional services is cost approximately 3,500.00 - 4,500.00.
The technique for medial branch blocks in the lumbar region requires a block of 2 medial branch nerves (MBN). The
recommendation is the following: (1) L1-L2 (T12 and L1 MBN); (2) L2-L3 (L1 and L2 MBN); (3) L3-L4 (L2 and L3
MBN); (4) L4-L5 (L3 and L4 MBN); (5) L5-S1: the L4 and L5 MBN are blocked, and it is recommended that S1 nerve
be blocked at the superior articular process. Blocking two joints such as L3-4 and L4-5 will require blocks of three
nerves (L2, L3 and L4). Blocking L4-5 and L5-S1 will require blocks of L3, L4, L5 with the option of blocking S1.
(Clemans, 2005) The volume of injectate for diagnostic medial branch blocks must be kept to a minimum (a trace
amount of contrast with no more than 0.5 cc of injectate), as increased volume may anesthetize other potential areas
of pain generation and confound the ability of the block to accurately diagnose facet pathology. Specifically, the
concern is that the lateral and intermediate branches will be blocked; nerves that innervate the paraspinal muscles
and fascia, ligaments, sacroiliac joints and skin. (Cohen, 2007) Intraarticular blocks also have limitations due to the
fact that they can be technically challenging, and if the joint capsule ruptures, injectate may diffuse to the epidural
space, intervertebral foramen, ligamentum flavum and paraspinal musculature. (Cohen, 2007) (aWashington, 2005)
(Manchikanti, 2003) (Dreyfuss, 2003) (BlueCross BlueShield, 2004) (Pneumaticos, 2006) (less than Boswell, 2007)
(Boswell2, 2007) A recent meta-analysis concluded that there is insufficient evidence to evaluate validity or utility of
diagnostic selective nerve root block, intra-articular facet joint block, medial branch block, or sacroiliac joint block as
diagnostic procedures for low back pain with or without radiculopathy. (Chou2, 2009) This study suggests that
proceeding to radiofrequency denervation without a diagnostic block is the most cost-effective treatment paradigm,
but does not result in the best pain outcomes. Cohen, 2010) See also Facet joint pain, signs and symptoms; Facet
joint radiofrequency neurotomy; Facet joint medial branch blocks (therapeutic injections); and Facet joint intra-
articular injections (therapeutic blocks). AlsoNeck Chapter and Pain Chapter. These are performed under
fluoroscopic guidance in a surgery center.
In the meantime, the patients condition is guarded.
I will see the patient for follow-up as scheduled.

JOHN, CARLOS DOB: 05/22/1986 (36 yo M) Acc No. 12570 DOS: 03/20/2023

patient may also benefit from epidural injections of their cervical spine. A series of epidural steroid injections to
relieve the symptoms by decreasing the nerve inflammation and alleviating the pain. This has a 70% success rate in
relieving radicular symptoms. These are performed under fluoroscopic guidance in a surgery center. These
procedures cost approximately $15,000 -17,500 each, which includes the cost of the surgical facility and the
anesthesiologist.

Criteria for the use of Epidural steroid injections, therapeutic: The purpose of ESI is to reduce pain and
inflammation, thereby facilitating progress in more active treatment programs, and avoiding surgery, but this
treatment alone offers no significant long-term functional benefit. (1) Radiculopathy must be documented by
physical examination and corroborated by imaging studies and/or electrodiagnostic testing. (2) Initially
unresponsive to conservative treatment (exercises, physical methods, NSAIDs and muscle relaxants). (3) Injections
should be performed using fluoroscopy (live x-ray) for guidance (4) In the therapeutic phase, repeat blocks should
only be offered if there is at least 50% pain relief for six to eight weeks, with a general recommendation of no more
than 4 blocks per region per year. (5) Repeat injections should be based on continued objective documented pain and
function response.

Criteria for the use of Epidural steroid injections, diagnostic: To determine the level of radicular pain, in cases where
diagnostic imaging is ambiguous, including the examples below: (1) To help to evaluate a pain generator when
physical signs and symptoms differ from that found on imaging studies; (2) To help to determine pain generators
when there is evidence of multi-level nerve root compression; (3)To help to determine pain generators when clinical
findings are suggestive of radiculopathy (e.g. dermatomal distribution), and imaging studies have suggestive cause
for symptoms but are inconclusive; (4) To help to identify the origin of pain in patients who have had previous spinal
surgery. The risks and complications were explained to the patient. They include but are not limited to: injection,
bleeding, neurovascular injury, failure to relieve symptoms, need for future re-operation, development of deep
venous thrombosis (blood clots), pulmonary embolism, development of reflex sympathetic dystrophy/complex
regional pain syndrome, cardiac arrest, cardiac arrhythmia, myocardial infarction, drug reactions including
cardiovascular, pulmonary, renal and hepatic, anesthesia complications including death. The patient understood and
wishes to proceed with the recommended procedure. These are performed under fluoroscopic guidance in a surgery
center. These procedures cost approximately $15,000-$17,500 each, which include the cost of the surgical facility
and the anesthesiologist. This includes the professional fee for the physician as well as monitored anesthesia, surgical
technician, fluoroscopy/x-ray technician, OR nurse, scrub technician, physician assistant well as Operating room
time, recovery room, recovery nurse, medication, operating room equipment, supplies, needs, etc. The professional
fee is $3500-$4500 for the surgeon. We will see the patient back in a few weeks for a repeat examination. The
patient's condition is guarded.

JOHN, CARLOS DOB: 05/22/1986 (36 yo M) Acc No. 12570 DOS: 10/29/2022

1. Others
Notes:
Mr. John is a pleasant 36-year-old gentleman who was in a motor vehicle accident on 12/15/2021. Since the accident, he has been
having continued complaints of neck and low back pain. He initially underwent a series of physical therapy regimens with only
mild relief of his symptoms. MRI of his cervical spine shows some mild loss of cervical lordosis with a disc bulge at C4-5 and C5-6.
If his neck pain continues, he is a candidate for cervical facet injections from C4 to C6. His biggest complaint continues to be pain
in his low back, right worse than left sided. MRI findings shows a L5-S1 listhesis with a right sided L5-S1 disc bulge. Given his
continued complaints of low back pain, we recommend he undergo a L5-S1 facet injection. Patient is agreeable and would like to
proceed with the injections as outlined per above. We will see him back in a few weeks

Procedures
LUMBAR FACET INJECTION:
These procedures cost approximately $15,000 -17,5000 each, which includes the cost of the surgical facility and the
anesthesiologist. Professional services is cost approximately 3,500.00 - 4,500.00.
The technique for medial branch blocks in the lumbar region requires a block of 2 medial branch nerves (MBN). The
recommendation is the following: (1) L1-L2 (T12 and L1 MBN); (2) L2-L3 (L1 and L2 MBN); (3) L3-L4 (L2 and L3 MBN); (4) L4-
L5 (L3 and L4 MBN); (5) L5-S1: the L4 and L5 MBN are blocked, and it is recommended that S1 nerve be blocked at the superior
articular process. Blocking two joints such as L3-4 and L4-5 will require blocks of three nerves (L2, L3 and L4). Blocking L4-5 and
L5-S1 will require blocks of L3, L4, L5 with the option of blocking S1. (Clemans, 2005) The volume of injectate for diagnostic
medial branch blocks must be kept to a minimum (a trace amount of contrast with no more than 0.5 cc of injectate), as increased
volume may anesthetize other potential areas of pain generation and confound the ability of the block to accurately diagnose facet
pathology. Specifically, the concern is that the lateral and intermediate branches will be blocked; nerves that innervate the
paraspinal muscles and fascia, ligaments, sacroiliac joints and skin. (Cohen, 2007) Intraarticular blocks also have limitations due
to the fact that they can be technically challenging, and if the joint capsule ruptures, injectate may diffuse to the epidural space,
intervertebral foramen, ligamentum flavum and paraspinal musculature. (Cohen, 2007) (aWashington, 2005) (Manchikanti,

are performed under fluoroscopic guidance in a surgery center. These procedures cost approximately $15,000-17,500 each, which
includes the cost of the surgical facility and the anesthesiologist.
Criteria for the use of Epidural steroid injections, therapeutic: The purpose of ESI is to reduce pain and inflammation, thereby
facilitating progress in more active treatment programs, and avoiding surgery, but this treatment alone offers no significant long-
term functional benefit. (1) Radiculopathy must be documented by physical examination and corroborated by imaging studies
and/or electrodiagnostic testing. (2) Initially unresponsive to conservative treatment (exercises, physical methods, NSAIDs and
muscle relaxants). (3) Injections should be performed using fluoroscopy (live x-ray) for guidance (4) In the therapeutic phase,
repeat blocks should only be offered if there is at least 50% pain relief for six to eight weeks, with a general recommendation of no
more than 4 blocks per region per year. (5) Repeat injections should be based on continued objective documented pain and
function response.
Criteria for the use of Epidural steroid injections, diagnostic: To determine the level of radicular pain, in cases where diagnostic
imaging is ambiguous, including the examples below: (1) To help to evaluate a pain generator when physical signs and symptoms
differ from that found on imaging studies; (2) To help to determine pain generators when there is evidence of multi-level nerve
root compression; (3)To help to determine pain generators when clinical findings are suggestive of radiculopathy (e.g.
dermatomal distribution), and imaging studies have suggestive cause for symptoms but are inconclusive; (4) To help to identify
the origin of pain in patients who have had previous spinal surgery. The risks and complications were explained to the patient.
They include but are not limited to: injection, bleeding, neurovascular injury, failure to relieve symptoms, need for future re-
operation, development of deep venous thrombosis (blood clots), pulmonary embolism, development of reflex sympathetic
dystrophy/complex regional pain syndrome, cardiac arrest, cardiac arrhythmia, myocardial infarction, drug reactions including
cardiovascular, pulmonary, renal and hepatic, anesthesia complications including death. The patient understood and wishes to
proceed with the recommended procedure. These are performed under fluoroscopic guidance in a surgery center. These
procedures cost approximately $15,000-$17,500 each, which include the cost of the surgical facility and the anesthesiologist. This
includes the professional fee for the physician as well as monitored anesthesia, surgical technician, fluoroscopy/x-ray technician,
OR nurse, scrub technician, physician assistant well as Operating room time, recovery room, recovery nurse, medication,
operating room equipment, supplies, needs, etc. The professional fee is $3500-$4500 for the surgeon. We will see the patient
back in a few weeks for a repeat examination. The patient's condition is guarded.

pages.summary: This is a Final Narrative Report dated March 8, 2022, from Jeff B. Tirsch, D.C., for patient Carlos Steve John. It details the patient's condition following a car accident on December 15, 2021, where he was a passenger in a rear-ended vehicle. The report describes the immediate aftermath, including transport to Northridge Hospital where initial tests were negative for acute pathology. The patient then sought care at Dr. Tirsch's office on December 16, 2021. The document lists the patient's subjective complaints, which include pain in the neck, back, and wrist, as well as headaches and fatigue.

JEFF B. TIRSCH, D.C.

FINAL NARRATIVE REPORT

March 8, 2022

RE:
Date of accident:

Carlos Steve John
December 15, 2021

Mr. Carlos Steve John was followed in my Woodland Hills office with regard to injuries that he
sustained on December 15, 2021. The following is a summary of my findings and conclusions.

HISTORY OF ACCIDENT:

Mr. John was the seatbelted right front seat passenger in a vehicle that was at a complete stop
for a red light on December 15, 2021, when the vehicle in which he was riding was rear-ended by
a large tow-truck. He was thrown about the interior of the vehicle, striking his head on a hard
surface within the vehicle; he denied loss of consciousness. Mr. John was immediately aware of
headaches and pain in his neck, mid-back, and lower back. Police and paramedics were
summoned to the scene, and the patient was transported by ambulance to Northridge Hospital.

An evaluation was performed in the emergency room of Northridge Hospital, and x-rays were
taken of the chest and a CT-scan of the brain was ordered. The chest x-rays revealed no evidence
of active cardiopulmonary disease. The CT-scan revealed no evidence of acute intracranial
pathology. Laboratory studies were performed, including a basic metabolic panel, a complete
blood count, and PT/PTT studies. At the time of discharge, Mr. John was provided with aftercare
instructions.

On the following day, December 16, 2021, Mr. John sought further medical care and treatment in
this office.

SUBJECTIVE COMPLAINTS:

Mr. John's primary complaint was sharp pain, weakness, and tenderness in the neck, mid-back,
and lower back. Headaches were present. The patient also complained of fatigue, nausea, and
difficulty concentrating. He also complained of sharp pain and weakness in the right wrist. His
symptoms increased with various movements and activities. Symptoms affected the patient's
ability to bend the involved areas. He had difficulty lifting or carrying heavier items. He also noted
difficulty driving or walking for long periods, before needing to rest.

The patient sustained injuries on December 15, 2021, which affected his work. A physical and orthopedic examination reveals findings related to the cervical spine, thoracic spine, and right wrist, including muscular spasm, tenderness, subluxation, restricted motion, and weakness. A prior motor vehicle accident in 2007 is also noted.

RE: JOHN, Carlos Steve
DATE: March 8, 2022
PAGE: 2

HEALTH STATUS PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT:
Prior to the aforementioned accident, Mr. John was not symptomatic in the involved regions. There
were no restrictions or limitations of any activities. The patient was not receiving any ongoing
medical treatment with regard to the injured body parts.

WORK HISTORY:
Mr. John was employed as a network manager and marketing director at the time of the
accident. He reported having to modify his work activities as a result of the injuries that he
sustained on December 15, 2021.

PAST PERTINENT MEDICAL HISTORY:
PRE-EXISTING OR PRIOR INJURIES: Motor vehicle accident in 2007.
CURRENT ILLNESSES: None.
SURGERIES: None.
DRUG ALLERGIES: None.
ALCOHOL: The patient consumes alcoholic beverages socially.
CIGARETTES: The patient does not use tobacco products.

PHYSICAL EXAMINATION:
Physical examination disclosed a well-developed, well-nourished 35-year-old male. His weight is
190 pounds, and his height is five feet, ten inches.

ORTHOPEDIC EXAMINATION:

CERVICAL SPINE:
Examination of the neck revealed muscular spasm and tenderness of the suboccipital muscles,
paracervical muscles, and trapezius muscles bilaterally. There were no obvious deformities. There
was subluxation of the cervical region. Motion of the vertebrae was restricted by muscle tension.
The patient expressed an increase in symptoms with movement of the neck. Shoulder depression
testing was positive. Foraminal distraction was positive, as was foraminal compression testing.

Cervical spine motion was restricted and painful, with flexion performed to 35 degrees (n=50);
extension performed to 40 degrees (n=60); lateral flexion performed to 30 degrees bilaterally
(n=45); and rotatory movements performed to 60 degrees bilaterally (n=80).

THORACIC SPINE:
There was pain elicited on palpation of the spinous processes and paravertebral muscles. There
was subluxation of the thoracic region. When the patient bent forward, it was apparent that joint
motion was restricted. No scars or gross deformities were observed. Thoracic rotations were
performed to 20 degrees bilaterally (n=30).

RIGHT WRIST:
There was tenderness to palpation over the right wrist, with motion reduced moderately. There
was 4/5 weakness at the right C6 wrist extensors/brachioradialis muscles.

There were no major deformities of the skin. There were no observable signs of vasculitis or

POSTURE:
The patient exhibited moderate anterior head displacement and moderate left head deviation.
There was mild-to-moderate rounding of the shoulders.

NEUROLOGICAL EVALUATION:
The patient was oriented to time, place and person. The patient had normal speech. Short term
memory appeared to be intact. Coordination was normal. Cranial nerves appeared to be intact.

Sensory functions were within normal boundaries. There was 4/5 weakness at the right C6 wrist
extensors/brachioradialis muscles; otherwise, there was normal strength in the upper and lower
extremities. Tone and bulk were normal. Reflexes were within normal limits.

COORDINATION:
Finger- to-nose, heel-to-shin, and rapid alternating movements were all performed normally.

CLINICAL COURSE:
Following my evaluation, a discussion was held with Mr. John regarding his condition and
treatment needs. He was advised to engage in a conservative treatment plan, with chiropractic
manipulative care with mobilization and muscle techniques to restore function of the affected
spinal regions. Adjunctive physiotherapeutic modalities were incorporated into the patient's
treatment regimen to promote healing. The modalities utilized included: Electrical muscle
stimulation, motorized and manual traction, moist heat packs, myofascial release, and chiropractic
manipulation. Home exercises were outlined, and the patient was provided with a booklet
containing instructions in specific exercises to stretch and strengthen the spine. Neurologic
consultation was advised, with respect to the patient's head injury. Work restrictions were
imposed, and work-related instructions were provided to Mr. John.

Currently, Mr. John reported some pain and stiffness in the neck, mid-back, and lower back. He
complained of persistent headaches and generalized fatigue. He also noted sharp pain and
weakness in the right wrist. Examination revealed subluxation of the cervical, thoracic, and
lumbar spine regions. Palpatory examination demonstrated spasm, tenderness, and tightness
over the suboccipital muscles on the right; paracervical muscles bilaterally; rhomboid muscles on
the right; trapezius muscles bilaterally; paradorsal muscles on the left; and paralumbar muscles.
There was tenderness to palpation over the right wrist. Mr. John had been able to return to full
duties at work. He was discharged from my service on March 8, 2022. He was instructed to
continue the home treatment measures, as previously detailed.

DIAGNOSES:

1. S06.0X0A Concussion Without Loss of Consciousness.

2. G44.209 Tension Headache, Unspecified. Not intractable, NOS

3. S13.4XXA Sprain of Ligaments of Cervical Spine

4. S23.4XXA Sprain of Ligaments of Thoracic Spine

5. S33.5XXA Sprain of Ligaments of Lumbar Spine

6. S63.501 Sprain of Right Wrist

DISCUSSION:

Mr. John sustained the above-described injuries as a direct result of the motor vehicle accident
that occurred on December 15, 2021. The patient's initial clinical presentation was consistent with
the mechanism of injury, as described. He required a multi-modality course of physiotherapy and
an exercise rehabilitation program aimed at improving the involved areas.

Since injuries heal with fibrous scar tissue, which lacks the elasticity or usability of the original
tissue, the patient will likely have residual weakness in the injured regions. It is a common
observation in cases such as this that exacerbations occur for seemingly mild external reasons.
This patient can anticipate recurrences of pain in the injured regions, which are more prevalent at
times of fatigue, stress or emotional upset.

I have encouraged this patient to continue with his stretching and strengthening exercise regimen
and to refrain from strenuous physical activity. I have provided Mr. John with educational materials
including a core exercise program and instructions to apply moist heat when the muscles of the
lower back become tight.

pages.summary: This document, dated March 8, 2022, is page 6 of a report for patient Carlos Steve John. It outlines the recommended future medical care and estimated costs for residual effects from a motor vehicle accident that occurred on December 15, 2021. The patient's conditions include a cerebral concussion, lumbar discopathy, and right wrist complaints. The proposed treatments range from chiropractic care, pain management consultations, and potential epidural steroid injections ($22,000 per injection) to spine surgery ($100,000-$300,000), neurologist follow-up, an MRI scan, and cortisone injections.

RE: JOHN, Carlos Steve
DATE: March 8, 2022
PAGE: 6

Of concern in this case were the symptoms associated with a cerebral concussion. Little
treatment is available for this type of injury, but symptoms generally tend to diminish with time.
Follow-up with a neurologist may be indicated, if symptoms persist unduly.

Mr. John indicated that he had gained weight following the subject motor vehicle accident. He was
encouraged to lose weight by following a sensible weight loss diet and exercise. I recommended
a gym membership to assist him in this regard.

Future medical care is required for the residual effects of the motor vehicle accident that occurred
on December 15, 2021. Future medical care shall be defined as follows:

1. Follow-up as needed with a chiropractic and/or medical physician for physical medicine
modalities, procedures, and general pain management. Best estimation for additional
costs over the next year due to residual chronic pain and associated exacerbations is
$1,500.00 to $3,000.00.

2. Co-medical management, such as consultation with a pain management specialist for
further evaluation of the patient's lumbar discopathy and any treatment, as recommended
by the pain management specialist, including lumbar epidural steroid injections to
decrease local pain and inflammation. Consultative evaluation by a pain management
specialist would be approximately $1,500.00.

3. Should epidural steroid injections be recommended by the pain management specialist,
the costs of such are estimated to be $22,000.00 per injection; these injections are
generally administered in a series of two to three.

4. Should epidural steroid injections be administered, without long-term benefit, spine
surgery consultation would be indicated for consideration of surgical intervention. The
costs associated with spine surgery can vary, depending on the procedure performed, and
can range from $100,000.00 to $300,000.00.

5. Continued co-medical management, such as consultative re-evaluation with a neurologist,
should symptoms associated with the cerebral concussion persist unduly. Consultative re-
evaluation by a neurologist would be approximately $1,000.00.

6. Co-medical management, such as consultation with an orthopedist for further evaluation
of the patient's protracted right wrist complaints and any treatment, as recommended by
the orthopedist. Consultative evaluation by an orthopedist would be approximately
$1,500.00.

7. Diagnostic testing may be indicated for evaluation of the patient's right wrist symptoms,
including a magnetic resonance imaging scan. Current costs associated with this type of
scan is $2,200.00.

8. Trigger injections and/or cortisone injections to help reduce residual pain and spasm may
be indicated, with respect to the right wrist. The estimated cost is $450.00 per injection,
which includes ultrasound guidance, physician fees, and pharmaceuticals.

pages.summary: This is a physical examination report for a patient named John Carlos, dated December 16, 2021. The patient presents with subjective complaints of headache, and pain in the left neck, middle back, left elbow, and wrist. The pain intensity is rated 7-8 out of 10 and interferes with daily activities by 75%. Objective findings from December 15, 2021, note muscle spasms and a positive Ortho test. The examination reveals restricted and painful range of motion in the cervical and lumbar spine. The diagnosis includes cervical/lumbar sprain/strain and a concussion. The document contains two CT Head scan reports from that day. The first report, resulted at 15:07 on 12/15/2021, indicated a suspected tiny anterior right frontal and temporal lobe subarachnoid hemorrhage. Patient Summary ED

SAFE PAIN MEDICINE PRESCRIBING

We care about you. Our goal is to treat your medical conditions, including pain, effectively, safely and in the right way.
Pain relief treatment can be complicated. Mistakes or abuse of pain medicine can cause serious health problems and death.
Our emergency department will only provide pain relief options that are safe and correct.
For your SAFETY, we routinely follow these rules when helping you with your pain.
1. 1. We look for and treat emergencies. We use our best judgement when treating pain. These recommendations follow legal and ethical advice.
2. 2. You should have only ONE provider and ONE pharmacy helping you with pain. We do not usually prescribe pain medication if you already receive pain medicine from another health care provider.
3. 3. If pain prescriptions are needed for pain, we will only give you a limited amount.
4. 4. We do not refill stolen or lost prescriptions for pain medication.
5. 5. We do not prescribe long-acting pain medicines such as: OxyContin, MSContin, Fentanyl (Duragesic), Methadone, Opana ER, Exalgo, and others.
6. 6. We do not provide missed doses of Methadone.
7. 7. We do not usually give shots for flare-ups of chronic pain.
8. 8. Health care laws, including HIPAA, allow us to ask for all of your medical records. These laws allow us to share information with other health providers who are treating you.
9. 9. We may ask you to show a photo ID when you receive a prescription for pain medicines.
10. 10. In California, we use the California Prescription Drug Monitoring Program called CURES. In Arizona and Nevada, we use the Prescription Monitoring Program that has oversight by the Arizona and Nevada state boards of pharmacy. These statewide computer systems track opioid pain medications and other controlled substance prescriptions.

Motor Vehicle Collision Injury, Adult
After a car accident (motor vehicle collision), it is common to have injuries to your head, face, arms, and body. These
injuries may include:
 Cuts.
 Burns.
 Bruises.
 Sore muscles or a stretch or tear in a muscle (strain).
 Headaches.

accident. These injuries often feel worse for the first 2448 hours. After that, you will usually begin to get better with
each day. How quickly you get better often depends on:
 How bad the accident was.
 How many injuries you have.
 Where your injuries are.
 What types of injuries you have.

Patient Summary ED

SAFE PAIN MEDICINE PRESCRIBING

We care about you. Our goal is to treat your medical conditions, including pain, effectively, safely and in the right way.
Pain relief treatment can be complicated. Mistakes or abuse of pain medicine can cause serious health problems and death.
Our emergency department will only provide pain relief options that are safe and correct.
For your SAFETY, we routinely follow these rules when helping you with your pain.
1. 1. We look for and treat emergencies. We use our best judgement when treating pain. These recommendations follow legal and ethical advice.
2. 2. You should have only ONE provider and ONE pharmacy helping you with pain. We do not usually prescribe pain medication if you already receive pain medicine from another health care provider.
3. 3. If pain prescriptions are needed for pain, we will only give you a limited amount.
4. 4. We do not refill stolen or lost prescriptions for pain medication.
5. 5. We do not prescribe long-acting pain medicines such as: OxyContin, MSContin, Fentanyl (Duragesic), Methadone, Opana ER, Exalgo, and others.
6. 6. We do not provide missed doses of Methadone.
7. 7. We do not usually give shots for flare-ups of chronic pain.
8. 8. Health care laws, including HIPAA, allow us to ask for all of your medical records. These laws allow us to share information with other health providers who are treating you.
9. 9. We may ask you to show a photo ID when you receive a prescription for pain medicines.
10. 10. In California, we use the California Prescription Drug Monitoring Program called CURES. In Arizona and Nevada, we use the Prescription Monitoring Program that has oversight by the Arizona and Nevada state boards of pharmacy. These statewide computer systems track opioid pain medications and other controlled substance prescriptions.

Motor Vehicle Collision Injury, Adult
After a car accident (motor vehicle collision), it is common to have injuries to your head, face, arms, and body. These
injuries may include:
 Cuts.
 Burns.
 Bruises.
 Sore muscles or a stretch or tear in a muscle (strain).
 Headaches.
You may feel stiff and sore for the first several hours. You may feel worse after waking up the first morning after the
accident. These injuries often feel worse for the first 24-48 hours. After that, you will usually begin to get better with
each day. How quickly you get better often depends on:
 How bad the accident was.
 How many injuries you have.
 Where your injuries are.
 What types of injuries you have.

Patient Summary ED

SAFE PAIN MEDICINE PRESCRIBING

We care about you. Our goal is to treat your medical conditions, including pain, effectively, safely and in the right way.
Pain relief treatment can be complicated. Mistakes or abuse of pain medicine can cause serious health problems and death.
Our emergency department will only provide pain relief options that are safe and correct.
For your SAFETY, we routinely follow these rules when helping you with your pain.
1. 1. We look for and treat emergencies. We use our best judgement when treating pain. These recommendations follow legal and ethical advice.
2. 2. You should have only ONE provider and ONE pharmacy helping you with pain. We do not usually prescribe pain medication if you already receive pain medicine from another health care provider.
3. 3. If pain prescriptions are needed for pain, we will only give you a limited amount.
4. 4. We do not refill stolen or lost prescriptions for pain medication.
5. 5. We do not prescribe long-acting pain medicines such as: OxyContin, MSContin, Fentanyl (Duragesic), Methadone, Opana ER, Exalgo, and others.
6. 6. We do not provide missed doses of Methadone.
7. 7. We do not usually give shots for flare-ups of chronic pain.
8. 8. Health care laws, including HIPAA, allow us to ask for all of your medical records. These laws allow us to share information with other health providers who are treating you.
9. 9. We may ask you to show a photo ID when you receive a prescription for pain medicines.
10. 10. In California, we use the California Prescription Drug Monitoring Program called CURES. In Arizona and Nevada, we use the Prescription Monitoring Program that has oversight by the Arizona and Nevada state boards of pharmacy. These statewide computer systems track opioid pain medications and other controlled substance prescriptions.

Motor Vehicle Collision Injury, Adult

After a car accident (motor vehicle collision), it is common to have injuries to your head, face, arms, and body. These injuries may include:

 Cuts.
 Burns.
 Bruises.
 Sore muscles or a stretch or tear in a muscle (strain).
 Headaches.

You may feel stiff and sore for the first several hours. You may feel worse after waking up the first morning after the accident. These injuries often feel worse for the first 24-48 hours. After that, you will usually begin to get better with each day. How quickly you get better often depends on:

 How bad the accident was.
 How many injuries you have.
 Where your injuries are.
 What types of injuries you have.

Patient Summary ED

SAFE PAIN MEDICINE PRESCRIBING

We care about you. Our goal is to treat your medical conditions, including pain, effectively, safely and in the right way.
Pain relief treatment can be complicated. Mistakes or abuse of pain medicine can cause serious health problems and death.
Our emergency department will only provide pain relief options that are safe and correct.
For your SAFETY, we routinely follow these rules when helping you with your pain.
1. 1. We look for and treat emergencies. We use our best judgement when treating pain. These recommendations follow legal and ethical advice.
2. 2. You should have only ONE provider and ONE pharmacy helping you with pain. We do not usually prescribe pain medication if you already receive pain medicine from another health care provider.
3. 3. If pain prescriptions are needed for pain, we will only give you a limited amount.
4. 4. We do not refill stolen or lost prescriptions for pain medication.
5. 5. We do not prescribe long-acting pain medicines such as: OxyContin, MSContin, Fentanyl (Duragesic), Methadone, Opana ER, Exalgo, and others.
6. 6. We do not provide missed doses of Methadone.
7. 7. We do not usually give shots for flare-ups of chronic pain.
8. 8. Health care laws, including HIPAA, allow us to ask for all of your medical records. These laws allow us to share information with other health providers who are treating you.
9. 9. We may ask you to show a photo ID when you receive a prescription for pain medicines.
10. 10. In California, we use the California Prescription Drug Monitoring Program called CURES. In Arizona and Nevada, we use the Prescription Monitoring Program that has oversight by the Arizona and Nevada state boards of pharmacy. These statewide computer systems track opioid pain medications and other controlled substance prescriptions.

Motor Vehicle Collision Injury, Adult

After a car accident (motor vehicle collision), it is common to have injuries to your head, face, arms, and body. These
injuries may include:

 Cuts.
 Burns.
 Bruises.
 Sore muscles or a stretch or tear in a muscle (strain).
 Headaches.

You may feel stiff and sore for the first several hours. You may feel worse after waking up the first morning after the
accident. These injuries often feel worse for the first 2448 hours. After that, you will usually begin to get better with
each day. How quickly you get better often depends on:

 How bad the accident was.
 How many injuries you have.
 Where your injuries are.
 What types of injuries you have.

Terms Used in this Form
"Hospital" means: Northridge Hospital Medical Center
"Patient" means the person registered to receive healthcare services.
"Patient's Legal Representative" can be the Patient's parent, guardian, conservator, or any other person
authorized to sign this document on the Patient's behalf, such as an agent under an advanced directive.
"We" or "Us" or "Our" refers to the Hospital.
"You" or "Your" refers to the person signing this document.
"Doctor" includes, but is not limited to, surgeons, radiologists, pathologists, emergency doctors, hospitalists,
anesthesiologists, intensive care doctors and other professionals authorized to recommend medical treatment
(including but not limited to nurse anesthetists, nurse mid-wives, physician assistants, and nurse practitioners).
By signing this form, You agree to all of the following provisions:
1. Consent to Medical and Surgical Procedures
You consent to the procedures that may be performed during the Patient's Hospital stay or provided to the Patient
as an outpatient. These procedures may include emergency treatment or services, laboratory procedures, X-ray
examinations, medical or surgical treatment or procedures, anesthesia, or other hospital services provided to the
Patient under the general and special instructions of the Patient's doctor. Some treatment or services may be
provided through telemedicine. You agree that the Hospital, its nursing staff and the Patient's doctors may access
and use the Patient's non-hospital pharmacy records in connection with the Patient's Hospital stay or outpatient
visit. You understand that the practice of medicine and surgery is not an exact science. You understand that
diagnosis and treatment may involve risks of injury or even death. You acknowledge that the Hospital makes no
guarantees about the results of examinations or treatments provided to the Patient in this Hospital. If the Patient
delivers an infant(s) at this Hospital, You agree that these same Conditions of Admission apply to the infant(s). You
also agree that these same Conditions of Admission apply to each outpatient visit for a course of treatment by the
Patient's Doctor, such as infusion for cancer or outpatient physical therapy.

You consent to the Hospital's use of photography, audio or video recording or other electronic imaging as required
for diagnosis or treatment of the Patient and for other internal Hospital purposes. We will not use the Patient's
image for marketing or fundraising unless We get Your separate authorization in writing. We may take the Patient's
picture to confirm and protect his/her identity for Hospital purposes.

nurse and the doctor agrees, You agree to make the arrangements at the expense of the Patient and, if applicable,
the Guarantor. The Hospital is not responsible for not providing a private duty nurse. You release the Hospital from
any and all liability based upon the use of a private duty nurse or the fact that the Hospital does not provide this
additional care.

We may participate in programs to teach resident doctors, medical students, student nurses, and/or other health

other professionals on the Hospital's staff and Your doctor.
5. Hospital's Legal Relationship to Doctors
Doctors are not employees or agents of the Hospital. They are independent practitioners who have been granted
the privilege of using the Hospital for the care and treatment of their patients. You may receive a separate bill
from these independent practitioners for their services.

general and special instructions.
6. Release of Information
You will be given a Notice of Privacy Practices that explains how the hospital may use information about the Patient.
The Notice of Privacy Practices is also available on the Hospital's website under Patient Privacy Notice. The Notice
of Privacy Practices explains that we will obtain Your written authorization to release information about the Patient,
unless We are allowed or required by law to disclose the information without authorization.
7. Personal Belongings
You should leave personal items at home. The Hospital has a fireproof safe for the safekeeping of money,
valuables, and other articles. The Hospital is not liable for the loss or damage to any money, valuables, or other

limited by law to five hundred dollars ($500) unless You request and receive a written receipt for a greater amount.

Subject to the limitations described below, the Patient and/or the Patient's Guarantor must pay the Hospital's Full
Charges for items, services and supplies provided to the Patient:

will bill or submit a claim to the Patient's Payor for all the items, services and supplies provided by the Hospital
to the Patient. Applicable copayments, coinsurance and deductibles must be paid by the Patient unless the
Patient receives financial assistance or discount under the Hospital's applicable policies which would reduce or
eliminate such payments. (See Section 9, below, regarding financial assistance and discounts offered by the
Hospital). The Hospital may request payment of applicable copayments, coinsurance and deductibles before or
at the time of service except with respect to care provided to treat emergency medical conditions. If the Payor
denies payment for all or part of the Hospital's bill, the Patient and/or the Guarantor will be required to pay
any amounts due to the Hospital. You also agree to, and hereby do, assign all the Patient's rights under the
Employee Retirement Income Security Act ("ERISA") or any other applicable state or federal law to Hospital to
Dignity Health.

d. Title to Property Used in Services. Title to all tangible items delivered to or used in providing services ("medical

the medical supplies are used in treating the Patient. Any warranty for that property is limited to the manufacturer's

9. Government-Sponsored Health Care Programs and Financial Assistance
The Hospital will assist uninsured Patients with applications for government-sponsored health care programs, such
as Medicare and Medicaid as well as other public and private health insurance or sponsorship programs, including
coverage offered through State or Federal Health Benefit Exchanges. In addition, the Hospital offers income-
based financial assistance under Dignity Health's Financial Assistance Policy and other discounts under Dignity
Health's Administrative Discounts Policy. Financial assistance includes free and discounted care based upon the
Patient's family income and medical expenses. Administrative discounts include an uninsured discount, prompt-pay
discount, hardship discount and special circumstances discount. If a Patient is uninsured and does not qualify for
government-sponsored health care programs or is insured but has high medical costs, financial assistance may be
available from Dignity Health to eliminate or substantially reduce the cost of medically necessary items, services
and supplies provided to the Patient. The Financial Assistance Policy, Plain Language Summary of the Financial
Assistance Policy, and Financial Assistance Application are located on each hospital facility's website and in public
areas throughout each facility. For more information about financial assistance and other discounts that may be
available to help pay for the cost of care provided to the Patient, the Patient may contact Dignity Health Patient
Financial Services or the Dignity Health Financial Counseling Office in person or at the telephone numbers listed
on the Plain Language Summary of the Financial Assistance Policy. To apply for financial assistance or another
discount from Dignity Health, the Patient must complete and submit an application and provide certain financial
information. Along with this Agreement, Patient will be offered a brochure that explains our billing process and a
copy of Dignity Health's Patient Financial Assistance Policy. The Hospital's financial counseling staff will also be
available to explain Dignity Health's policies and to assist Patient with the financial assistance application process.
10. Third Party Liability
If the Hospital provides services to the Patient for injuries caused by the actions of others, the Hospital may have
the right to seek payment from such third parties and to assert a lien for the Hospital's charges for emergency and
ongoing medical services provided to the Patient from the person or entity that is financially responsible for damages
related to the injury. You agree to provide us the name of any person or entity that may have caused the Patient's
injuries, the name of the person's insurance company, the name of the Patient's lawyer, if any, and any other
information that may help the Hospital exercise its lien rights and to cooperate with the Hospital in exercising the
Hospital's lien rights.
11. Worker's Compensation
If the Hospital provides services to the Patient for injuries related to the Patient's employment, the Hospital may
have the right to assert a lien on any worker's compensation recovery for the Patient's hospital and medical
expenses. You agree to provide Hospital with information that may help the Hospital assert a lien on any worker's
compensation recovery and to cooperate with the Hospital in exercising those rights.
Dignity Health.

Patient Education Materials:
JOHN, CARLOS STEVE has been given the following patient education materials:
Head Injuries, Adult
You have had a head injury which does not appear serious at this time. A concussion is a state of changed mental ability, usually from a blow to the head. You should take clear liquids for the rest of the day and then resume your regular diet. You should not take sedatives or alcoholic beverages for 24 hours. After injuries such as yours, most problems occur within the first 24 hours.

THESE MINOR SYMPTOMS MAY BE SEEN AFTER DISCHARGE:
 Memory difficulties
 Dizziness
 Headaches
 Double vision
 Hearing difficulties
 Depression
 Tiredness
 Weakness
 Difficulty with concentration
If you experience any of these problems, you should not be alarmed. A bruise on the brain (concussion) requires a few days for recovery. This is the same as a bruise elsewhere on the body. Many patients with head injuries frequently experience such symptoms. Usually, these problems disappear without medical care. If symptoms last for more than one day, notify your caregiver. See your caregiver sooner if symptoms are becoming worse rather than better.

 Clean your wound or burn as told by your doctor.
  o Wash it with mild soap and water.
  o Rinse it with water to get all the soap off.
  o Pat it dry with a clean towel. Do not rub it.
  o If you were told to put an ointment or cream on the wound, do so as told by your doctor.
 Follow instructions from your doctor about how to take care of your wound or burn. Make sure you:
  o Know when and how to change or remove your bandage (dressing).
  o Always wash your hands with soap and water before and after you change your bandage. If you cannot use soap and water, use hand sanitizer.
  o Leave stitches (sutures), skin glue, or skin tape (adhesive) strips in place, if you have these. They may need to stay in place for 2 weeks or longer. If tape strips get loose and curl up, you may trim the loose edges.
    Do not remove tape strips completely unless your doctor says it is okay.
 Do not:
  o Scratch or pick at the wound or burn.
  o Break any blisters you may have.
  o Peel any skin.
 Avoid getting sun on your wound or burn.
 Raise (elevate) the wound or burn above the level of your heart while you are sitting or lying down. If you have a wound or burn on your face, you may want to sleep with your head raised. You may do this by putting an extra pillow under your head.
 Check your wound or burn every day for signs of infection. Check for:
  o More redness, swelling, or pain.
  o More fluid or blood.

   Depression or mood swings.
   Feeling worried or nervous (anxiety).
   Getting upset or bothered easily.
   Memory problems.
   Trouble concentrating or paying attention.
   Sleep problems.
   Feeling tired all the time.

   A change in your ability to control your pee or poop (stool).

   Chest pain.

Carlos S. John is a 35-year-old male, who presents today for an evaluation of his low back pain due to a motor vehicle accident that occurred on December 15, 2021 at 12:00 p.m. The patient was the restrained front seat passenger of a Dodge. He states that they were at an intersection and waiting for the light to turn green when they were rear ended and pushed forward. This caused them to hit the car in front. Three vehicles were involved in the accident. No police report was taken. Upon impact, the airbags did not deploy. He denied loss of consciousness. He noted whiplash to the head. Immediately after the accident, he felt dizzy. Gradually, over hours, he experienced right-sided low back pain. An ambulance arrived at the scene of the accident and he was taken to Northridge ER on the same day. A CT scan of was performed. He stayed in the hospital for a few hours. pages.summary: This is a progress note for patient Carlos S. John (DOB: 05/22/1986) from a visit on 06/10/2022 with Dr. Leia Rispoli of Interventional Pain Medicine. The patient presents with several weeks of debilitating radicular symptoms. After a 45-minute telemedicine consultation, Dr. Rispoli recommends an INTERLAMINAR L5-S1 epidural steroid injection and continued physical/chiropractic therapy. The patient consented to the procedure. The visit was billed under CPT code 99204 for a new patient office visit lasting 45-59 minutes. The document was e-signed by Dr. Rispoli on 06/10/2022.

Given patient clinical history and physical exam findings, I recommend patient pursue INTERLAMINAR L5-S1 epidural steroid injection for both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes. I also recommend patient continue guided physical therapy/chiropractic care as tolerated, during this treatment plan.

This patient is suffering from several weeks of debilitating radicular symptoms, impacting the daily life and ADLs. Patient has had either the inability to tolerate noninvasive conservative care, or failure to respond to at least four weeks of noninvasive conservative care including PT/chiropractic care, rest, activity modification, heat/ice, Massage, NSAIDs or tylenol.

The patient denies recent or current antibiotic use or infections, and was advised to call and cancel any procedure appointments if the patient becomes ill or is prescribed antibiotics within 7 days of the procedure. Anticoagulant medication list was reviewed with patient and appropriate protocol was taken in preparation for procedure. The patient would like to proceed as noted above after discussing the risks, benefits, and alternatives to these injections.

This plan was discussed in full detail with patient. I spent 45 minutes with at least 70% directly with patient discussing history, physical exam, reviewing imaging, and treatment protocol in full detail, as well as reviewing alternative treatment options. Risks and benefits were also discussed in full details.

Due to risks of COVID19, this appointment was conducted through a telemedicine/phone platform.
